COVID-19_analysis

Introduction

Now we will expand on the lessons from the first part of the workshop and apply the skills we learned to the recent COVID-19 data which has been curated by the Johns Hopkins University Centor fo Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE). We will recreate some of the data they made with their Tableau dashboard from the raw data available on Google Sheets or GitHub. For the purposes of this workshop I took the data from 2020-02-10 and cleaned it (the code used to clean the data is in the 03.Rmd file) so we could focus on learning the concepts.

library(tidyverse)
library(ggsci)
data <- read_csv("COVID19.csv")

Let’s try to see if we can aggregate the data similar to the Tableau dashboard. We can use the group_by(), summarize(), and arrange() functions to add up all the confirmed cases by country. 

data %>% 
  group_by(Country) %>% 
  summarize(total = sum(Confirmed_no)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(total))

Let’s try to visualize the data! First, we will have to aggregate the data using group_by() and summarize().

data %>% 
  group_by(Location, Date) %>% 
  summarize(total = sum(Confirmed_no)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Date, y = total, color = Location)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_color_nejm()
